  "A solubility curve is a graph showing how the solubility of a substance (y-axis, usually in g/100 mL) changes with temperature (x-axis, in degrees C).": "",
  "A point below the solubility curve represents:": "",
  "An unsaturated solution that can dissolve more": "",
  "A saturated solution at maximum dissolved solute": "",
  "A supersaturated solution with excess dissolved": "",
  "An insoluble substance that cannot dissolve at all": "",
  "Points below the curve represent unsaturated solutions because they contain less solute than the maximum possible at that temperature.": "",
  "A point on the solubility curve represents:": "",
  "A saturated solution at that temperature": "",
  "A suspension of particles in the solvent": "",
  "A supersaturated and unstable solution": "",
  "An unsaturated solution needing more solute": "",
  "Points on the curve represent saturated solutions, where the maximum amount of solute is dissolved at that specific temperature.": "",
  "A point above the solubility curve represents:": "",
  "An unsaturated solution with room for more solute": "",
  "A saturated solution at maximum concentration level": "",
  "A supersaturated solution (unstable, excess dissolved)": "",
  "An impossible solution that cannot exist at all": "",
  "Points above the curve represent supersaturated solutions where more solute is dissolved than normally possible. These are unstable and can crystallize.": "",
