  "What is a solubility curve?": "",
  "A straight line showing the density of different solutions at one temperature": "",
  "A graph showing the maximum solubility of a substance at various temperatures": "",
  "A diagram showing the molecular structure of a solute in its crystal form": "",
  "A table listing all the substances that dissolve in water at room temperature": "",
  "A solubility curve is a graphical representation showing the maximum amount of a solute that can dissolve in a solvent at different temperatures.": "",
  "What does the term 'grams per 100 mL of water' mean on a solubility curve?": "",
  "It means the total mass of the entire solution mixture in the beaker": "",
  "It means the mass of solute that dissolves in 100 mL of water at that temperature": "",
  "It means the volume of solute needed to fill 100 mL of empty container": "",
  "It means the mass of water needed to dissolve 100 grams of any solute": "",
  "The unit g/100 mL water on a solubility curve tells you how many grams of solute can dissolve in 100 mL of water at a specific temperature to form a saturated solution.": "",
  "What does a steep slope on a solubility curve indicate?": "",
  "Temperature has little effect on the solubility of that solute": "",
  "Solubility changes rapidly with small temperature changes": "",
  "The substance is insoluble at all temperatures on the graph": "",
  "The substance is a gas whose solubility decreases with heat": "",
  "A steep slope means solubility is very sensitive to temperature. A small temperature change causes a large change in the amount that can dissolve.": "",
  "What does a flat (nearly horizontal) solubility curve indicate?": "",
  "The substance is insoluble at every temperature shown on the graph": "",
  "Temperature has very little effect on the solubility of that substance": "",
  "The substance is extremely soluble at every single temperature": "",
  "The substance changes between solid and gas rapidly at all temperatures": "",
  "A flat solubility curve means that changing the temperature does not significantly change how much solute dissolves. NaCl is a well-known example.": "",
  "Define 'solubility' as represented on a solubility curve.": "",
  "The speed at which a substance dissolves in the solvent": "",
  "The maximum amount of solute that can dissolve at a specific temperature": "",
  "The minimum temperature needed to dissolve any amount of solute": "",
  "The total volume of solution produced when all solute is dissolved": "",
  "On a solubility curve, solubility represents the maximum mass of solute (in grams) that can dissolve in a fixed amount of solvent (usually 100 mL of water) at a given temperature.": "",
  "What does 'crystallization' mean in the context of solubility curves?": "",
  "The process of dissolving more solute into an unsaturated solution": "",
  "The process where excess dissolved solute comes out of solution as solid": "",
  "The process of heating a solution to increase its temperature only": "",
  "The process of evaporating all the solvent from a solution sample": "",
  "Crystallization occurs when dissolved solute separates from solution and forms solid crystals. This happens when a solution is cooled below the temperature needed to keep all the solute dissolved.": "",
  "What does 'intersection point' on overlapping solubility curves mean?": "",
  "Both substances become insoluble at that specific temperature": "",
  "Both substances have the same solubility at that specific temperature": "",
  "Both substances form a chemical reaction at that specific temperature": "",
  "Both substances crystallize out of solution at the same exact moment": "",
  "When two solubility curves intersect, both substances have identical solubilities at that temperature. Above or below that point, one substance is more soluble than the other.": "",
  "What is 'recrystallization' and how does it use solubility curves?": "",
  "A purification technique that dissolves a substance in hot solvent then cools to crystallize": "",
  "The process of crushing crystals into powder to increase their surface area": "",
  "A method of heating a solid until it melts into a liquid at high temperature": "",
  "The process of mixing two different crystal types together in one container": "",
  "Recrystallization uses the difference in solubility at different temperatures. A substance is dissolved in hot solvent (where solubility is high) then cooled, causing pure crystals to form.": "",
  "What does it mean when a substance has 'inverse solubility'?": "",
  "The substance becomes more soluble as temperature increases": "",
  "The substance becomes less soluble as temperature increases": "",
  "The substance has exactly the same solubility at all temperatures": "",
  "The substance does not dissolve in any solvent at any temperature": "",
  "Inverse solubility means solubility decreases as temperature increases. This is typical for gases and a few unusual solids like Ce2(SO4)3.": "",
  "What does 'saturation point' mean on a solubility curve?": "",
  "The point where no solute will ever dissolve regardless of conditions": "",
  "The exact amount of solute shown on the curve at a given temperature": "",
  "The temperature at which all solute evaporates from the solution": "",
  "The pressure at which the solvent begins to boil at that temperature": "",
  "The saturation point is the exact solubility value shown on the curve at a particular temperature. It represents the boundary between unsaturated and supersaturated regions.": "",
  "A student looks at a solubility curve and sees that KNO3 has a solubility of 30 g/100 mL at 20 degrees C. She dissolves 25 g in 100 mL at 20 degrees C. What type of solution does she have?": "",
